WEBVTT

1
00:00:06.006 --> 00:00:08.965
♪ slow. haunting music ♪

2
00:00:33.946 --> 00:00:35.948
♪ music swells ♪

3
00:00:55.925 --> 00:00:57.970
♪♪♪

4
00:01:10.113 --> 00:01:11.984
♪ gentle music ♪

5
00:01:12.115 --> 00:01:14.117
[birds chirping]

6
00:01:29.219 --> 00:01:31.221
[birds calling]

7
00:01:42.580 --> 00:01:44.582
♪♪♪

8
00:02:08.737 --> 00:02:10.478
Nice one.

9
00:02:10.608 --> 00:02:12.915
Not very happy about
the hook in his dinner.

10
00:02:17.702 --> 00:02:19.226
Catch him on a hopper?

11
00:02:20.792 --> 00:02:22.316
Hopper's out yet?

12
00:02:22.446 --> 00:02:24.100
There's one out.

13
00:02:25.101 --> 00:02:27.843
Yeah. they're sure not buying
this salmonfly.

14
00:02:27.973 --> 00:02:30.106
[Paul] They're not buying
your presentation.

15
00:02:30.237 --> 00:02:34.066
You're slapping the water
with it. Just lay it.

16
00:02:34.154 --> 00:02:35.894
Too much action in your wrist.

17
00:02:36.025 --> 00:02:38.114
[chuckling] Stop trying
to hail a cab on Fifth Avenue.

18
00:02:38.245 --> 00:02:39.507
[chuckles]

19
00:02:39.637 --> 00:02:42.553
Just lay it down.

20
00:02:43.989 --> 00:02:45.774
Like that.

21
00:02:49.038 --> 00:02:50.605
[grunts]

22
00:02:52.346 --> 00:02:53.521
[laughs softly]

23
00:02:53.651 --> 00:02:55.218
And on a hopper.

24
00:02:55.349 --> 00:02:56.698
I do this for a living.
big brother.

25
00:02:56.828 --> 00:02:58.308
Well. sort of.

26
00:02:58.439 --> 00:03:00.005
You should do it for a living.

27
00:03:00.136 --> 00:03:01.616
Never make work
of your passions.

28
00:03:01.746 --> 00:03:03.792
Well. counterpoint to that is:
love what you do.

29
00:03:03.922 --> 00:03:05.576
you never work a day
in your life.

30
00:03:05.707 --> 00:03:08.231
-You love what you do?
-I don't even like what I do.

31
00:03:08.362 --> 00:03:09.624
You should analyze that.

32
00:03:09.754 --> 00:03:10.973
[Preston]
That's exactly what I'm doing.

33
00:03:11.103 --> 00:03:12.496
[Paul]
Glad you're doing something.

34
00:03:12.627 --> 00:03:14.194
'cause you damn sure
ain't catching any trout.

35
00:03:17.980 --> 00:03:20.548
You better not be doing
what I think you're doing.

36
00:03:21.636 --> 00:03:24.029
-Tying on a nymph.
-Don't you dare!

37
00:03:24.160 --> 00:03:25.944
This is my last day. Paul.

38
00:03:26.075 --> 00:03:27.816
I'm tying on a nymph.

39
00:03:27.946 --> 00:03:29.774
And if you fuck with me
even a little.

40
00:03:29.905 --> 00:03:31.515
I'm putting on a streamer.

41
00:03:31.646 --> 00:03:33.300
-I don't know you anymore.
-[chuckles]

42
00:03:33.430 --> 00:03:35.127
I recognize your face.

43
00:03:35.258 --> 00:03:38.000
but the words coming from it
are the words of a stranger.

44
00:03:44.963 --> 00:03:46.269
-Ha!
-Doesn't count.

45
00:03:46.400 --> 00:03:47.618
[Preston]
It counts.

46
00:03:47.749 --> 00:03:49.403
[Paul]
I got a spincaster in the truck.

47
00:03:49.533 --> 00:03:51.143
Why don't you just put
some cheese on a treble hook.

48
00:03:51.274 --> 00:03:53.537
Get out of here. [laughs]

49
00:03:54.886 --> 00:03:56.061
[grunts]

50
00:03:56.192 --> 00:03:58.194
-[chuckles]
-[chuckles] Hey.

51
00:03:58.325 --> 00:03:59.761
I'm keeping it.

52
00:03:59.891 --> 00:04:02.459
Course you are.
fucking fish killer.

53
00:04:02.590 --> 00:04:05.070
I'm keeping it.
and you're cooking it.

54
00:04:05.201 --> 00:04:08.117
[chuckles]
All right.

55
00:04:08.248 --> 00:04:10.685
And lay it out there.

56
00:04:10.815 --> 00:04:13.514
[laughing]

57
00:04:13.688 --> 00:04:15.690
♪ gentle music ♪

58
00:04:24.307 --> 00:04:27.092
♪ dramatic music ♪

59
00:04:31.488 --> 00:04:33.403
-[siren wailing]
-[cell phone ringing]

60
00:04:36.101 --> 00:04:38.321
Hey. I have the Hermès scarf
and the blouse from Brunello.

61
00:04:38.452 --> 00:04:40.410
I'm meeting her
at the Greenwich.

62
00:04:40.541 --> 00:04:42.717
and then we'll depart
for the opening at five-fifteen.

63
00:04:42.847 --> 00:04:44.109
Well. does her assistant know?

64
00:04:44.240 --> 00:04:46.634
Okay. yeah. calling now.

65
00:04:48.897 --> 00:04:50.942
-[man grunts]
-[Paige grunts. groans]

66
00:04:51.073 --> 00:04:52.596
[whimpering]

67
00:04:56.208 --> 00:04:57.819
[gasping]

68
00:05:00.474 --> 00:05:01.605
[sobs]

69
00:05:04.739 --> 00:05:06.001
[groans]

70
00:05:07.872 --> 00:05:10.135
[Charlotte] <i>The Washington</i>
<i>Heights Women's Center</i>

71
00:05:10.266 --> 00:05:12.094
 <i>will provide essential services</i>

72
00:05:12.224 --> 00:05:15.315
for New York's
most underprivileged

73
00:05:15.445 --> 00:05:18.013
and underrepresented
demographic.

74
00:05:18.143 --> 00:05:20.145
Beyond reproductive care.

75
00:05:20.276 --> 00:05:22.626
the Women's Center
will provide wellness care.

76
00:05:22.757 --> 00:05:25.499
counseling.
dietary consultation...

77
00:05:25.629 --> 00:05:27.588
[quietly]
The nutritionist was my idea.

78
00:05:27.718 --> 00:05:29.807
The diet of some of those people
is abhorrent.

79
00:05:29.938 --> 00:05:31.679
They just don't know any better.

80
00:05:31.809 --> 00:05:33.507
[quietly] They don't eat junk
because they like it. Laura.

81
00:05:33.637 --> 00:05:35.726
They eat it because it's cheap.

82
00:05:35.857 --> 00:05:37.946
They don't need a nutritionist.
They need better food.

83
00:05:38.076 --> 00:05:41.341
[scoffs] The food bank has
a bigger selection of produce

84
00:05:41.471 --> 00:05:43.473
than my Whole Foods. Stacy.
and that all rots.

85
00:05:43.604 --> 00:05:45.345
They won't eat it.

86
00:05:45.475 --> 00:05:48.086
They want chips and chicken
nuggets. sugarcoated cereals.

87
00:05:48.217 --> 00:05:49.566
They need education.

88
00:05:49.697 --> 00:05:51.568
[cell phone ringing quietly]

89
00:05:51.699 --> 00:05:53.614
Excuse me.

90
00:05:54.658 --> 00:05:56.138
[sighs]

91
00:05:58.096 --> 00:05:59.402
Paige?

92
00:05:59.533 --> 00:06:00.882
[Paige]
<i>I was attacked.</i>

93
00:06:01.012 --> 00:06:02.536
Attacked?

94
00:06:02.666 --> 00:06:04.581
A man just walked up and hit me.

95
00:06:04.712 --> 00:06:06.104
 <i>Took my bags and hit me.</i>

96
00:06:06.235 --> 00:06:07.323
-Oh. my--
<i>-Can you see it?</i>

97
00:06:07.454 --> 00:06:08.672
Did you call the police?

98
00:06:08.803 --> 00:06:10.674
-It just happened.
<i>-Where are you?</i>

99
00:06:10.805 --> 00:06:12.459
Uh. downtown.

100
00:06:12.589 --> 00:06:13.938
-Get in a cab.
<i>-Should I go to the hospital?</i>

101
00:06:14.069 --> 00:06:16.245
-Like. look at this.
<i>-No.</i>

102
00:06:16.376 --> 00:06:17.464
Go to Dr. Steele's office.
I'll meet you there.

103
00:06:17.594 --> 00:06:18.813
 <i>Wait. There's a police car.</i>

104
00:06:20.554 --> 00:06:22.425
♪ dramatic music ♪

105
00:06:23.948 --> 00:06:26.168
[panting]

106
00:06:26.298 --> 00:06:27.822
What happened?

107
00:06:27.952 --> 00:06:29.563
I was attacked and robbed.

108
00:06:29.693 --> 00:06:32.043
-Somebody hit you?
-Hit me and took two bags.

109
00:06:32.174 --> 00:06:34.306
-shopping bags.
-Uh. what'd they look like?

110
00:06:34.437 --> 00:06:36.265
Uh. maybe 30.

111
00:06:36.396 --> 00:06:39.529
A navy sweatshirt.
hood over his head. tall.

112
00:06:39.660 --> 00:06:41.401
-tall and skinny.
-What color was he?

113
00:06:41.531 --> 00:06:43.403
Color?

114
00:06:43.533 --> 00:06:44.926
His skin.

115
00:06:45.056 --> 00:06:47.842
I... I can't. I-I can't.

116
00:06:47.972 --> 00:06:49.278
You didn't notice?

117
00:06:49.409 --> 00:06:52.455
Was he dark like me
or light like him?

118
00:06:54.457 --> 00:06:57.155
I don't know.
I only saw him walking away.

119
00:06:57.286 --> 00:06:59.201
But you think he's 30.
How you know that?

120
00:06:59.331 --> 00:07:02.422
I-I saw for an instant. but yes.
he looked 30 or maybe younger.

121
00:07:02.552 --> 00:07:05.207
but I don't want to say his race
because I don't know.

122
00:07:05.337 --> 00:07:06.643
How about this?

123
00:07:06.774 --> 00:07:08.079
What color were
the shopping bags?

124
00:07:08.210 --> 00:07:09.559
White. two of them.

125
00:07:09.690 --> 00:07:11.735
Navy blue sweatshirt.
two white bags.

126
00:07:11.866 --> 00:07:14.042
-Got it.
-[sighs]

127
00:07:14.172 --> 00:07:15.391
You need to file a report.

128
00:07:15.522 --> 00:07:16.871
[siren wailing]

129
00:07:17.001 --> 00:07:18.916
[Paige]
Are you still there?

130
00:07:21.702 --> 00:07:24.095
One-seventeen Park Avenue.

131
00:07:24.226 --> 00:07:25.619
[tires squealing]

132
00:07:30.537 --> 00:07:31.842
[Paige]
How many stitches?

133
00:07:31.973 --> 00:07:33.148
[Dr. Steele]
I think it's gonna take six.

134
00:07:33.278 --> 00:07:35.585
[sighs] How big a scar?

135
00:07:35.716 --> 00:07:37.152
We'll deal with the scar later.

136
00:07:37.282 --> 00:07:39.110
It's easy for you to say.
It's not on your face.

137
00:07:39.241 --> 00:07:40.285
[Stacy]
Russell might like it.

138
00:07:40.416 --> 00:07:41.635
Scars are sexy.

139
00:07:41.765 --> 00:07:43.158
Scars on men are sexy.

140
00:07:43.288 --> 00:07:45.726
Scars on women are...

141
00:07:45.856 --> 00:07:47.902
I'm gonna look like
a battered spouse.

142
00:07:48.032 --> 00:07:49.556
I don't know why
you were walking.

143
00:07:49.686 --> 00:07:50.861
Why were you walking?
You know better than that.

144
00:07:50.992 --> 00:07:52.646
I was on Fifth Avenue. Mom.

145
00:07:52.776 --> 00:07:54.691
If you can't walk on Fifth
Avenue. where can you walk?

146
00:07:54.822 --> 00:07:56.084
You can't.
That's the whole point.

147
00:07:57.825 --> 00:07:59.174
Did you call Daddy?

148
00:07:59.304 --> 00:08:00.480
-No. he's fishing.
-And that means

149
00:08:00.610 --> 00:08:01.916
-you can't call him?
-No. honey.

150
00:08:02.046 --> 00:08:03.918
I can call him.
I just can't reach him.

151
00:08:04.048 --> 00:08:05.789
He doesn't have cell service
on the river.

152
00:08:05.920 --> 00:08:07.356
He'll call tonight.

153
00:08:07.487 --> 00:08:09.097
But I can tell you
what he'll say.

154
00:08:09.227 --> 00:08:10.402
He'll say take the car.

155
00:08:10.533 --> 00:08:12.404
-[sighs]
-[Dr. Steele] Stay still.

156
00:08:13.928 --> 00:08:15.930
He hit me.

157
00:08:16.060 --> 00:08:17.279
For no reason.

158
00:08:17.409 --> 00:08:19.150
I would have given him the bags.

159
00:08:19.281 --> 00:08:20.456
I know.

160
00:08:20.587 --> 00:08:22.240
-He just hit me.
-[quietly] I know.

161
00:08:25.809 --> 00:08:28.420
♪ majestic music ♪

162
00:08:51.226 --> 00:08:53.271
♪♪♪

163
00:09:00.975 --> 00:09:02.542
[sighs]

164
00:09:04.413 --> 00:09:06.371
[Paul] Just leave all that shit
on the plane.

165
00:09:06.502 --> 00:09:08.330
I got a surprise for you
tomorrow.

166
00:09:08.460 --> 00:09:11.768
[sighs]
Paul. I have to leave tomorrow.

167
00:09:11.899 --> 00:09:14.466
You're fishing
the Big Lost tomorrow.

168
00:09:14.597 --> 00:09:17.034
You have to pack into
the Big Lost. [stammers]

169
00:09:17.165 --> 00:09:19.776
I fly in the smoke jumpers.
and we can use their strip.

170
00:09:24.259 --> 00:09:25.782
Happy birthday.

171
00:09:28.393 --> 00:09:30.134
[chuckles]

172
00:09:30.265 --> 00:09:31.875
Oh. shit.

173
00:09:32.006 --> 00:09:33.398
[chuckles]

174
00:09:37.925 --> 00:09:39.404
-Ah.
-[chuckles]

175
00:09:39.535 --> 00:09:43.539
[laughing]

176
00:09:43.670 --> 00:09:45.236
-Ah.
-Baby.

177
00:09:45.367 --> 00:09:46.716
-Yeah.
-Baby.

178
00:09:46.847 --> 00:09:48.196
-Soft.
-Oh.

179
00:09:48.326 --> 00:09:49.327
Soft.

180
00:09:49.458 --> 00:09:51.286
[laughing]

181
00:09:51.460 --> 00:09:53.505
♪♪♪

182
00:10:09.870 --> 00:10:11.436
[thunder rumbling softly]

183
00:10:11.567 --> 00:10:13.090
[door opens]

184
00:10:19.836 --> 00:10:21.838
[Paul]
Sixty-four.

185
00:10:24.362 --> 00:10:26.843
[chuckles softly]

186
00:10:26.974 --> 00:10:29.759
Astonishing where the time goes.

187
00:10:29.890 --> 00:10:31.935
I wonder.

188
00:10:32.066 --> 00:10:35.591
what do I have. maybe ten.
15 years before I'm too old

189
00:10:35.722 --> 00:10:39.247
to do anything more
than just remember?

190
00:10:39.377 --> 00:10:40.640
[Preston grunts softly]

191
00:10:47.603 --> 00:10:50.780
I took Stacy and the kids
to this resort in the Caribbean.

192
00:10:52.826 --> 00:10:55.002
Rooms are ten grand a night.

193
00:10:55.132 --> 00:10:56.264
Villas are 30.

194
00:10:56.394 --> 00:10:57.744
This shit doesn't impress me.

195
00:10:57.874 --> 00:10:59.136
No. Paul.
it doesn't impress me either.

196
00:10:59.267 --> 00:11:01.486
I'm just trying
to tell you a story.

197
00:11:01.617 --> 00:11:03.227
-[chuckles]
-Now...

198
00:11:03.358 --> 00:11:06.709
if you quantify making it
by the things you can afford.

199
00:11:06.840 --> 00:11:09.669
then this place is
making it. yeah?

200
00:11:09.799 --> 00:11:11.496
We're sitting there
on the beach

201
00:11:11.627 --> 00:11:14.456
and watching all these couples
walk by.

202
00:11:15.979 --> 00:11:18.199
We're the youngest there
by. like. two decades.

203
00:11:18.329 --> 00:11:21.724
I mean. everyone's
in their 70s and 80s.

204
00:11:21.855 --> 00:11:24.509
Barely waddle across the sand.

205
00:11:26.076 --> 00:11:29.123
All covered up in their big hats
and their long-sleeved shirts.

206
00:11:29.253 --> 00:11:31.212
They'd made it.

207
00:11:32.517 --> 00:11:35.999
But their bodies are too old
to enjoy it.

208
00:11:36.130 --> 00:11:38.132
Flew halfway around the world.

209
00:11:38.262 --> 00:11:40.264
and they were
too old and crippled.

210
00:11:41.309 --> 00:11:45.400
Swim the water. run in the sand.
make love. none of it.

211
00:11:45.530 --> 00:11:47.489
They finally made it.

212
00:11:48.620 --> 00:11:51.711
They were all too old
to create a single memory.

213
00:11:54.061 --> 00:11:56.019
And they knew it.

214
00:11:57.412 --> 00:11:59.414
It was on every one
of their faces.

215
00:12:00.850 --> 00:12:02.156
Saw them at the restaurant.

216
00:12:02.286 --> 00:12:04.854
Same thing.
Not a smile among them.

217
00:12:04.985 --> 00:12:06.987
'Cause they knew.

218
00:12:09.163 --> 00:12:11.687
They worked their whole lives
for that moment.

219
00:12:13.733 --> 00:12:16.126
The moment had already
passed them by.

220
00:12:19.086 --> 00:12:20.435
That's why I'm here.

221
00:12:20.565 --> 00:12:22.742
That's why I quit.

222
00:12:24.265 --> 00:12:26.223
I make a memory a day. brother.

223
00:12:26.354 --> 00:12:28.269
Sometimes more.

224
00:12:28.399 --> 00:12:31.925
But make them for who. huh?

225
00:12:32.969 --> 00:12:34.057
Hmm?

226
00:12:34.188 --> 00:12:35.624
No kids.

227
00:12:35.755 --> 00:12:37.844
No... no wife.

228
00:12:37.974 --> 00:12:40.890
You-you... you got nobody
to share it with. Paul.

229
00:12:41.021 --> 00:12:42.370
I'm sharing it with you
right now.

230
00:12:42.500 --> 00:12:43.893
Once a year.
you share it with me.

231
00:12:44.024 --> 00:12:45.373
Then you should come more often.

232
00:12:45.503 --> 00:12:48.115
[scoffs]
At least get a girlfriend.

233
00:12:48.245 --> 00:12:49.638
[chuckles]
Not on your life.

234
00:12:49.769 --> 00:12:52.336
[sighs]
How about a dog?

235
00:12:52.467 --> 00:12:54.208
They're needier
than girlfriends.

236
00:12:54.338 --> 00:12:56.210
Maybe a goldfish. then.

237
00:12:56.340 --> 00:12:58.734
-[chuckles] Maybe.
-Huh.

238
00:12:58.865 --> 00:13:00.344
You'd probably try to kill it

239
00:13:00.475 --> 00:13:02.346
with one of
your giant hook streamers.

240
00:13:02.477 --> 00:13:05.480
[both laughing]

241
00:13:09.136 --> 00:13:10.790
[Preston]
<i>True.</i>[laughing]

242
00:13:10.964 --> 00:13:12.966
♪ gentle music ♪

243
00:13:23.411 --> 00:13:25.587
-Thank you. Mmm.
-[lively chatter]

244
00:13:25.717 --> 00:13:27.850
Oh. sorry. [clears throat]

245
00:13:27.981 --> 00:13:30.070
[pop music playing quietly]

246
00:13:31.811 --> 00:13:33.160
Abby. how was your day?

247
00:13:33.290 --> 00:13:35.162
Laser resurfacing is
the most effective.

248
00:13:35.292 --> 00:13:37.207
Doesn't that make your skin
shiny. like. forever?

249
00:13:37.338 --> 00:13:39.122
[Russell]
I still haven't seen it.

250
00:13:39.253 --> 00:13:40.645
[Paige] You're never seeing it.
Looks like a bloody zipper.

251
00:13:40.776 --> 00:13:41.951
I wish I had been there.
[scoffs]

252
00:13:42.082 --> 00:13:43.648
What. so he could've
hit you. too?

253
00:13:43.779 --> 00:13:45.737
All you would've gotten is
shot. stabbed or worse.

254
00:13:45.868 --> 00:13:47.217
What's worse than getting shot?

255
00:13:47.348 --> 00:13:48.784
I don't know. but
that's what would have happened.

256
00:13:48.915 --> 00:13:50.655
-Being set on fire is worse.
-[Stacy] Girls.

257
00:13:50.786 --> 00:13:52.135
-please. can we just--
-[Paige] And then the police.

258
00:13:52.266 --> 00:13:54.050
they just kept asking.
"What was his race?"

259
00:13:54.181 --> 00:13:56.052
Like that has anything
to do with it.

260
00:13:56.183 --> 00:13:57.314
I mean. it's pretty
important information

261
00:13:57.445 --> 00:13:58.446
when you're trying
to find somebody.

262
00:13:58.576 --> 00:14:01.275
-Whoa.
-That's so racist.

263
00:14:01.405 --> 00:14:03.233
-[scoffs]
-[cell phone ringing]

264
00:14:06.062 --> 00:14:07.455
[Paige]
Where are you going?

265
00:14:07.585 --> 00:14:09.109
It's your father.

266
00:14:09.239 --> 00:14:10.719
So? Where are you going?

267
00:14:10.850 --> 00:14:14.070
It is rude to talk on the phone
in a restaurant.

268
00:14:14.201 --> 00:14:16.116
It is also rude to play

269
00:14:16.246 --> 00:14:18.292
on your phone in a restaurant
and surf the Internet.

270
00:14:18.422 --> 00:14:22.383
Basically. what all of you
are doing right now is rude.

271
00:14:22.513 --> 00:14:23.906
Rude to who?

272
00:14:24.037 --> 00:14:26.082
It's rude to me.
It's rude to each other.

273
00:14:26.213 --> 00:14:27.692
It's rude to the staff.

274
00:14:27.823 --> 00:14:29.869
Just fucking rude.

275
00:14:31.914 --> 00:14:34.656
[horns honking]

276
00:14:34.786 --> 00:14:37.137
[gasps]
It's so bright there.

277
00:14:37.267 --> 00:14:39.400
-What time is it?
<i>-Seven.</i>

278
00:14:40.749 --> 00:14:41.750
Full moon.

279
00:14:41.881 --> 00:14:44.796
 <i>Wow. Look at those stars.</i>

280
00:14:46.407 --> 00:14:47.495
 <i>My view's better.</i>

281
00:14:47.625 --> 00:14:48.975
[scoffs]
Well.

282
00:14:49.105 --> 00:14:50.367
until your brother
gets indoor plumbing.

283
00:14:50.498 --> 00:14:52.195
I'll have to take
your word for it.

284
00:14:52.326 --> 00:14:54.284
Oh. there's plumbing of sorts.

285
00:14:54.415 --> 00:14:55.851
[sighs] Got a sink.

286
00:14:55.982 --> 00:14:58.201
-Got a shower now.
<i>-Well. until</i>

287
00:14:58.332 --> 00:15:00.856
the outhouse moves indoors.

288
00:15:00.987 --> 00:15:03.032
then I'll have to rely
on pictures.

289
00:15:03.163 --> 00:15:04.729
 <i>You feel rested?</i>

290
00:15:04.860 --> 00:15:06.775
 <i>What time do you land tomorrow?</i>

291
00:15:06.906 --> 00:15:09.343
Okay. gonna have to push it
back a day. honey.

292
00:15:09.473 --> 00:15:11.519
because Paul has something very.

293
00:15:11.649 --> 00:15:13.260
 <i>very special planned</i>
<i>for tomorrow.</i>

294
00:15:13.390 --> 00:15:15.218
-Mm-hmm.
<i>-It's a stretch of river</i>

295
00:15:15.349 --> 00:15:16.741
 <i>that can only be reached</i>
<i>by packhorse.</i>

296
00:15:16.872 --> 00:15:18.874
Takes. like. a week.

297
00:15:19.005 --> 00:15:21.224
Paul has permission
to fly us into it.

298
00:15:21.355 --> 00:15:23.096
Honey. this is like...

299
00:15:23.226 --> 00:15:25.228
Well. it's virgin water.

300
00:15:25.359 --> 00:15:26.621
Oh. now there's
virgins involved.

301
00:15:26.751 --> 00:15:28.188
[Preston laughs]

302
00:15:28.318 --> 00:15:31.147
Nobody fishes this stretch.
honey. Nobody.

303
00:15:31.278 --> 00:15:34.237
Maybe a dozen people a year.
if that.

304
00:15:34.368 --> 00:15:37.545
 <i>Hey. um. some bad news.</i>

305
00:15:37.675 --> 00:15:41.375
 <i>Uh. Paige got mugged today</i>
<i>down in the Village.</i>

306
00:15:41.505 --> 00:15:43.203
What? Mugged?

307
00:15:43.333 --> 00:15:44.856
-Is she okay?
<i>-Yeah.</i>

308
00:15:44.987 --> 00:15:47.511
She just. you know.
she got a pretty good shiner and

309
00:15:47.642 --> 00:15:49.035
 <i>a decent cut.</i>

310
00:15:49.165 --> 00:15:50.906
 <i>The doctor saw her.</i>
<i>Six stitches.</i>

311
00:15:51.037 --> 00:15:55.041
Goddamn it. I cannot come up
with one plausible reason

312
00:15:55.171 --> 00:15:57.521
-why we still live in that city.
<i>-Well.</i>

313
00:15:57.652 --> 00:15:59.175
I'll give you two.

314
00:15:59.306 --> 00:16:00.568
Our children.

315
00:16:00.698 --> 00:16:03.614
Two more.
Our grandchildren. my parents.

316
00:16:03.745 --> 00:16:06.356
 <i>Make her use the car. honey.</i>
<i>That's what it's for.</i>

317
00:16:06.487 --> 00:16:09.925
[sighs] She thinks
it's a garish display of wealth.

318
00:16:10.056 --> 00:16:11.535
[sighs] Well.
if my money's so offensive.

319
00:16:11.666 --> 00:16:13.450
maybe we should stop
giving it to her.

320
00:16:13.581 --> 00:16:15.191
-Oh. honey.
<i>-No. I'm serious.</i>

321
00:16:15.322 --> 00:16:17.193
 <i>Sell her apartment</i>
<i>and put her up in a house</i>

322
00:16:17.324 --> 00:16:19.979
in Great Neck.
or she takes the fucking car.

323
00:16:20.109 --> 00:16:21.632
 <i>Yeah. I knew</i>
<i>you were gonna do this.</i>

324
00:16:21.763 --> 00:16:23.765
-What am I doing?
<i>-Okay. let's--</i>

325
00:16:23.895 --> 00:16:25.941
This problem will be right here
when you get back.

326
00:16:26.072 --> 00:16:27.508
Let's deal with it then.

327
00:16:27.638 --> 00:16:29.075
[sighs] All right.

328
00:16:29.205 --> 00:16:30.815
She's okay. though. huh?

329
00:16:30.946 --> 00:16:33.775
 <i>Yes. In the meantime.</i>
<i>enjoy your mountains.</i>

330
00:16:33.905 --> 00:16:37.213
 <i>enjoy your brother.</i>
<i>enjoy the hole in the ground</i>

331
00:16:37.344 --> 00:16:40.303
he thinks is a toilet.
and I'll see you Monday.

332
00:16:40.434 --> 00:16:42.218
Monday.

333
00:16:42.349 --> 00:16:43.524
I love you. honey.

334
00:16:43.654 --> 00:16:45.395
Love you.

335
00:17:04.371 --> 00:17:05.937
So. Russell.
anything interesting

336
00:17:06.068 --> 00:17:07.852
happen in your world today.

337
00:17:07.983 --> 00:17:10.246
besides your wife
getting mugged?

338
00:17:10.377 --> 00:17:12.292
[stammers] Uh...

339
00:17:13.728 --> 00:17:15.643
Uh. yeah. we're. uh...

340
00:17:15.773 --> 00:17:19.690
Well. we're. uh. we're investing
in a Dutch cargo ship venture.

341
00:17:19.821 --> 00:17:21.301
I mean.
some of these larger vessels.

342
00:17:21.431 --> 00:17:23.912
they. uh. carry
over 25.000 containers.

343
00:17:24.043 --> 00:17:26.262
Like. 2.000 and change
per container.

344
00:17:26.393 --> 00:17:28.569
That's over 50 million a load
in freight.

345
00:17:28.699 --> 00:17:31.702
And you have crew fees
and docking fees. fuel by far

346
00:17:31.833 --> 00:17:33.530
being the largest expense--

347
00:17:33.661 --> 00:17:36.968
So... no.
nothing interesting happened.

348
00:17:38.361 --> 00:17:42.409
Excuse me. Um. can I order
a martini. gin. three olives?

349
00:17:42.539 --> 00:17:44.063
[quietly]
Thank you.

350
00:17:47.153 --> 00:17:49.198
What's wrong with you?

351
00:17:49.329 --> 00:17:51.026
I was the one that got punched.

352
00:17:51.200 --> 00:17:54.334
♪ majestic music ♪

353
00:18:15.268 --> 00:18:17.270
♪♪♪

354
00:18:27.628 --> 00:18:28.803
[Paul]
Let's go.

355
00:18:31.719 --> 00:18:32.894
-Prest?
-Yeah.

356
00:18:33.024 --> 00:18:34.330
You might want to grab your rod.

357
00:18:34.461 --> 00:18:35.766
Oh. shit. Christ.

358
00:18:35.897 --> 00:18:38.769
[panting]

359
00:18:40.858 --> 00:18:42.295
The way you talk
about this place.

360
00:18:42.425 --> 00:18:44.471
I thought
I'd only need my net. so...

361
00:18:44.601 --> 00:18:46.647
[both laugh]

362
00:18:47.909 --> 00:18:49.954
♪ gentle music ♪

363
00:19:05.753 --> 00:19:07.755
♪♪♪

364
00:19:20.420 --> 00:19:21.943
Hey.

365
00:19:22.073 --> 00:19:24.032
Caddis are hatching.

366
00:19:44.705 --> 00:19:46.663
♪♪♪

367
00:20:01.678 --> 00:20:03.506
Up! Yeah!

368
00:20:08.642 --> 00:20:10.687
Oh.

369
00:20:16.302 --> 00:20:17.738
[laughs]

370
00:20:27.138 --> 00:20:28.792
It's gonna be
one of those days. brother.

371
00:20:28.923 --> 00:20:29.967
-[Preston] Good.
-[laughs]

372
00:20:30.098 --> 00:20:31.882
I could use one.

373
00:20:45.853 --> 00:20:47.811
♪♪♪

374
00:21:03.131 --> 00:21:05.525
[birds chirping and calling]

375
00:21:10.617 --> 00:21:11.879
That worry you at all?

376
00:21:14.795 --> 00:21:16.710
We're not going that way.

377
00:21:16.840 --> 00:21:20.061
'Cause that storm sure looks
like it's coming this way.

378
00:21:20.191 --> 00:21:22.281
There wasn't any weather
on the radar this morning.

379
00:21:22.411 --> 00:21:24.718
[chuckles] Well. there's weather
there now. Paul.

380
00:21:24.848 --> 00:21:26.676
Storms build over the mountains
every afternoon.

381
00:21:28.156 --> 00:21:29.592
But we're going that way.

382
00:21:30.985 --> 00:21:32.987
[thunder rumbling softly]

383
00:21:33.117 --> 00:21:35.206
We can leave now if you want.

384
00:21:36.251 --> 00:21:38.427
I don't ever want to leave.

385
00:21:40.386 --> 00:21:42.997
♪ slow. gentle music ♪

386
00:22:01.232 --> 00:22:03.409
Can't do it
any better than that.

387
00:22:25.431 --> 00:22:27.041
[grunting]

388
00:22:30.131 --> 00:22:31.872
Ah.

389
00:22:32.002 --> 00:22:33.352
-[line snaps]
-Oh. no!

390
00:22:33.482 --> 00:22:34.570
No!

391
00:22:34.701 --> 00:22:36.267
[groans]

392
00:22:36.398 --> 00:22:38.661
[laughs] I just h...
it was a monster!

393
00:22:38.792 --> 00:22:39.662
[Paul]
We should go.

394
00:22:39.793 --> 00:22:41.490
[thunder rumbling]

395
00:22:43.144 --> 00:22:44.232
Yeah.

396
00:22:44.406 --> 00:22:46.582
♪ suspenseful music ♪

397
00:22:46.713 --> 00:22:47.931
Shit!

398
00:22:53.459 --> 00:22:55.591
[plane whirring]

399
00:23:09.562 --> 00:23:11.390
What do you think? What-what's
this telling you here?

400
00:23:11.520 --> 00:23:13.392
[Paul] I'm just gonna pick
my way through it.

401
00:23:13.522 --> 00:23:15.785
It's gonna be a little bumpy
over the mountains.

402
00:23:15.916 --> 00:23:17.787
Yeah. Okay.

403
00:23:26.056 --> 00:23:28.102
♪♪♪

404
00:23:35.849 --> 00:23:37.851
[thunder rumbling]

405
00:23:49.123 --> 00:23:51.125
[thunder rumbling]

406
00:23:58.654 --> 00:24:01.178
[plane shuddering]

407
00:24:05.792 --> 00:24:07.794
♪♪♪

408
00:24:17.934 --> 00:24:19.370
[exhales sharply]

409
00:24:23.984 --> 00:24:25.986
[thunder rumbling]

410
00:24:29.380 --> 00:24:30.773
[alarm beeps]

411
00:24:32.819 --> 00:24:34.473
[alarm beeps]

412
00:24:42.045 --> 00:24:43.482
Jesus!

413
00:24:43.612 --> 00:24:44.874
Yep.

414
00:24:45.962 --> 00:24:47.486
[alarm beeping]

415
00:24:53.840 --> 00:24:55.537
[thunder rumbling]

416
00:24:57.800 --> 00:25:00.455
Big Sky Approach.
this is Cessna 185 Bravo Zulu.

417
00:25:00.586 --> 00:25:02.239
I need a SWAP.

418
00:25:02.370 --> 00:25:03.589
[woman] <i>Copy. Nancy-Bravo.</i>
<i>Speed and altitude?</i>

419
00:25:03.719 --> 00:25:06.156
One-thirty knots at 8.200.

420
00:25:06.287 --> 00:25:08.681
 <i>Maintain southwest heading.</i>
<i>climb to 11.000.</i>

421
00:25:08.811 --> 00:25:11.640
Copy that. Eleven thousand.
Thank you. tower.

422
00:25:11.771 --> 00:25:13.033
We'll get up over this.

423
00:25:14.425 --> 00:25:16.253
[thunder rumbling]

424
00:25:16.427 --> 00:25:18.517
♪ dramatic music ♪

425
00:25:25.393 --> 00:25:26.612
Jesus!

426
00:25:26.742 --> 00:25:28.135
-Fuck. Paul!
-Hold on.

427
00:25:30.920 --> 00:25:32.748
[Preston]
Christ.

428
00:25:32.879 --> 00:25:34.358
Stacy!

429
00:25:34.489 --> 00:25:36.926
-Wait. where was she?
-Five blocks from here.

430
00:25:37.057 --> 00:25:38.101
Middle of the day.

431
00:25:38.232 --> 00:25:39.494
[scoffs]

432
00:25:41.191 --> 00:25:44.586
Politicians in this city
have guilted us into chaos.

433
00:25:44.717 --> 00:25:46.022
Michael wants us
to move to Connecticut.

434
00:25:46.153 --> 00:25:47.850
-Mm.
-Or just stay in the Hamptons

435
00:25:47.981 --> 00:25:50.070
year-round.
and I'm running out of excuses.

436
00:25:50.200 --> 00:25:51.506
The kids are gone.

437
00:25:51.637 --> 00:25:53.203
He can work from anywhere
these days.

438
00:25:53.334 --> 00:25:55.205
Well. why don't you?

439
00:25:55.336 --> 00:25:56.685
'Cause our marriage
wouldn't last a month.

440
00:25:56.816 --> 00:25:58.774
-Oh. stop it.
-[laughs softly]

441
00:25:58.905 --> 00:25:59.993
I'd have to learn
how to cook. for one.

442
00:26:00.123 --> 00:26:01.864
Oh. God forbid. yeah.

443
00:26:01.995 --> 00:26:04.388
And what in the world
would we talk about?

444
00:26:04.519 --> 00:26:05.781
All of our friends are here.
the ones

445
00:26:05.912 --> 00:26:07.827
-that haven't moved to Florida.
-Yeah.

446
00:26:08.871 --> 00:26:11.700
Hmm. This is my city.

447
00:26:11.831 --> 00:26:13.223
It has gone to hell before.

448
00:26:13.354 --> 00:26:15.225
It will come back.
It always does.

449
00:26:15.356 --> 00:26:17.488
Now. you. on the other hand.

450
00:26:17.619 --> 00:26:20.796
how you keep your mountain man
in Manhattan.

451
00:26:20.927 --> 00:26:22.798
that is a trick
that you must show me.

452
00:26:22.929 --> 00:26:24.626
Our daughters is the trick.

453
00:26:24.757 --> 00:26:26.672
He would never leave them.

454
00:26:26.802 --> 00:26:29.718
and he will never get
the girls to leave. so...

455
00:26:29.849 --> 00:26:32.242
-[laughs] No.
-No. he just. as long as he gets

456
00:26:32.373 --> 00:26:33.809
his little escapes.

457
00:26:33.940 --> 00:26:36.116
But you have to wonder
why we choose to live

458
00:26:36.246 --> 00:26:38.031
in a place we need to escape.

459
00:26:38.161 --> 00:26:40.511
Because there's no stock
exchange in Telluride. my dear.

460
00:26:40.642 --> 00:26:42.905
Whenever I see Michael
looking at properties online.

461
00:26:43.036 --> 00:26:45.125
I just. I just remind him
how far that is

462
00:26:45.255 --> 00:26:47.823
from Yankee Stadium.
and that usually does it.

463
00:26:47.954 --> 00:26:51.087
[laughs] You'd have to stock
the Hudson with trout

464
00:26:51.218 --> 00:26:52.915
-to entice mine.
-[laughs]

465
00:26:53.046 --> 00:26:54.874
Just buy him a little cabin
in the Catskills.

466
00:26:55.004 --> 00:26:57.659
I think they invented
fly-fishing there.

467
00:26:57.790 --> 00:26:59.095
It's just three hours away.

468
00:26:59.226 --> 00:27:00.923
He can go there
whenever he wants.

469
00:27:01.054 --> 00:27:02.795
It's easier to get there
than the Hamptons.

470
00:27:02.925 --> 00:27:05.624
You realize all we ever
talk about is leaving.

471
00:27:05.754 --> 00:27:08.235
-It's all anyone talks about.
-Well. of course we do.

472
00:27:08.365 --> 00:27:10.063
We're New Yorkers. What else
are we gonna talk about

473
00:27:10.193 --> 00:27:11.847
if we can't complain
about our city?

474
00:27:11.978 --> 00:27:14.197
[phone vibrating]

475
00:27:15.242 --> 00:27:17.200
-Hmm.
-Hmm?

476
00:27:17.331 --> 00:27:18.724
Do we know anyone in Idaho?

477
00:27:18.854 --> 00:27:20.943
The Greenbergs have
a house in Sun Valley.

478
00:27:21.944 --> 00:27:23.337
Yeah. Preston didn't call me
last night.

479
00:27:23.467 --> 00:27:25.513
I'm just gonna. um...

480
00:27:26.862 --> 00:27:28.603
Hello?

481
00:27:28.734 --> 00:27:31.171
[Shepherd]
<i>Is this Mrs. Clyburn?</i>

482
00:27:31.301 --> 00:27:32.912
It is.

483
00:27:33.042 --> 00:27:34.783
Who's this?

484
00:27:34.914 --> 00:27:37.656
 <i>I'm Officer Shepherd with </i>
<i>the U.S. Department of Forestry.</i>

485
00:27:39.614 --> 00:27:41.398
Yes?

486
00:27:41.529 --> 00:27:44.358
 <i>Is your husband Preston Clyburn?</i>

487
00:27:46.316 --> 00:27:47.622
Yes.

488
00:27:47.753 --> 00:27:49.580
[Shepherd clears throat]

489
00:27:49.711 --> 00:27:52.322
 <i>Ma'am. your husband was involved</i>
<i>in a plane crash on a mountain</i>

490
00:27:52.453 --> 00:27:54.281
 <i>-called Borah Peak.</i>
-[gasps]

491
00:27:56.849 --> 00:27:58.285
Uh. can I... is...

492
00:27:58.415 --> 00:27:59.678
[stammers softly]

493
00:27:59.808 --> 00:28:02.289
Can I speak to him?
Is he all right?

494
00:28:02.419 --> 00:28:03.899
 <i>No. ma'am.</i>

495
00:28:04.073 --> 00:28:06.206
♪ slow. somber music ♪

496
00:28:06.336 --> 00:28:07.729
 <i>I'm sorry to say</i>
<i>both he and a Paul Clyburn</i>

497
00:28:07.860 --> 00:28:09.078
 <i>did not survive the crash.</i>

498
00:28:09.209 --> 00:28:10.123
[gasps]

499
00:28:10.253 --> 00:28:11.124
Stacy?

500
00:28:11.254 --> 00:28:14.040
[gasping]

501
00:28:14.170 --> 00:28:15.432
 <i>Uh. ma'am?</i>

502
00:28:17.565 --> 00:28:19.088
What do I do? What do I...

503
00:28:19.219 --> 00:28:20.829
 <i>Well. ma'am.</i>
<i>we'd like you to come here</i>

504
00:28:20.960 --> 00:28:22.570
 <i>and identify the bodies.</i>

505
00:28:22.701 --> 00:28:24.006
 <i>Help arrange transport</i>
<i>to wherever you choose</i>

506
00:28:24.137 --> 00:28:26.487
 <i>-as their resting place.</i>
-[crying]

507
00:28:26.617 --> 00:28:29.446
Hi. This is Stacy's friend.
What's happened?

508
00:28:29.577 --> 00:28:31.710
[sniffles]

509
00:28:31.840 --> 00:28:32.928
Uh...

510
00:28:33.059 --> 00:28:35.975
Okay. uh. just let... uh. um...

511
00:28:36.105 --> 00:28:38.281
-Let me get that.
-[silverware clatters]

512
00:28:38.412 --> 00:28:41.284
[breathing heavily]

513
00:28:41.415 --> 00:28:42.938
Uh...

514
00:28:43.069 --> 00:28:45.114
Uh. I-Idaho Falls.

515
00:28:45.245 --> 00:28:46.681
Is there an airport?

516
00:28:48.639 --> 00:28:50.598
Okay. Okay. [sobs]

517
00:28:50.729 --> 00:28:52.078
Oh. honey.

518
00:28:52.208 --> 00:28:54.036
I'm so--
-I just. just...

519
00:28:54.167 --> 00:28:55.603
just-just let me...

520
00:28:57.561 --> 00:28:59.172
[loud clattering]

521
00:29:00.173 --> 00:29:02.175
[crying]

522
00:29:05.439 --> 00:29:07.484
♪♪♪

523
00:29:33.162 --> 00:29:34.381
I'll get the car.

524
00:29:39.429 --> 00:29:40.953
Mom.

525
00:29:41.083 --> 00:29:43.738
They just think it's him.
They don't know.

526
00:29:43.869 --> 00:29:46.175
-Paige.
-What? They don't.

527
00:29:46.306 --> 00:29:48.308
-Please.
-[Macy] They look like pilgrims.

528
00:29:48.438 --> 00:29:50.440
-[phone vibrating]
-[Bridgett] Where are we?

529
00:29:53.008 --> 00:29:54.227
Hey.

530
00:29:55.663 --> 00:29:58.100
I texted and I left a message.

531
00:29:59.362 --> 00:30:02.104
This is a little more important
than school. don't you think?

532
00:30:02.235 --> 00:30:05.455
I can't include you in decisions
when you do not respond.

533
00:30:05.586 --> 00:30:07.240
I will tell you why.

534
00:30:07.370 --> 00:30:09.982
Because he is my fucking father
and they are my children.

535
00:30:10.112 --> 00:30:11.722
When people talk about
life-altering events.

536
00:30:11.853 --> 00:30:13.768
they are talking about this.

537
00:30:13.899 --> 00:30:15.814
Then get on a plane
and come get them.

538
00:30:16.858 --> 00:30:19.078
Yeah. that's what I thought.

539
00:30:19.208 --> 00:30:20.427
[clears throat]

540
00:30:22.298 --> 00:30:23.996
♪ slow. dramatic music ♪

541
00:30:34.354 --> 00:30:36.356
♪♪♪

542
00:30:48.585 --> 00:30:50.892
Would you like to check in
at the hotel?

543
00:30:51.023 --> 00:30:54.069
Deal with the rest
in the morning?

544
00:30:54.200 --> 00:30:56.550
Take me to the coroner.
I want to get this over with.

545
00:31:01.337 --> 00:31:03.339
-Would you like some music?
-I would not.

546
00:31:03.470 --> 00:31:04.732
Okay.

547
00:31:17.919 --> 00:31:19.834
Do we all go in?

548
00:31:19.965 --> 00:31:21.444
I don't know. Uh...

549
00:31:22.489 --> 00:31:24.708
Let me get the lay of the land.

550
00:31:32.586 --> 00:31:33.892
[sniffles]

551
00:31:37.025 --> 00:31:38.113
[Shepherd]
Ma'am.

552
00:31:38.244 --> 00:31:39.941
we're very sorry for your loss.

553
00:31:40.986 --> 00:31:42.335
Walk me through this.

554
00:31:42.465 --> 00:31:44.119
[Hastings]
You knew the brother as well?

555
00:31:44.250 --> 00:31:46.121
-[Stacy] I did.
-The state requires

556
00:31:46.252 --> 00:31:48.602
that remains
be positively identified

557
00:31:48.732 --> 00:31:50.517
by a relative or close friend.

558
00:31:50.647 --> 00:31:53.999
Someone with enough familiarity
to make visual recognition.

559
00:31:54.129 --> 00:31:55.609
Won't take long.

560
00:31:56.653 --> 00:31:58.612
♪ slow. somber music ♪

561
00:32:09.014 --> 00:32:11.016
♪♪♪

562
00:32:22.418 --> 00:32:24.246
[door opens]

563
00:32:32.080 --> 00:32:33.952
There's no other way?

564
00:32:35.431 --> 00:32:36.955
I mean. clearly.
you know who it is

565
00:32:37.085 --> 00:32:39.261
or you wouldn't have known
to contact me.

566
00:32:39.392 --> 00:32:41.524
We found a phone. ma'am.

567
00:32:41.655 --> 00:32:44.266
That does not
positively identify a body.

568
00:32:44.397 --> 00:32:46.616
But why else
would he have the phone?

569
00:32:47.878 --> 00:32:51.491
I don't make the laws. ma'am.
but I do have to enforce them.

570
00:32:53.101 --> 00:32:55.538
You're gonna force me.

571
00:32:58.367 --> 00:33:00.239
[sighs]

572
00:33:00.369 --> 00:33:03.764
[voice breaking]
Before he left. he kissed me.

573
00:33:03.894 --> 00:33:05.505
[breath trembles]

574
00:33:05.635 --> 00:33:07.072
And he smiled.

575
00:33:07.202 --> 00:33:09.857
and that is the last image
of him in my mind.

576
00:33:09.988 --> 00:33:11.728
If...

577
00:33:11.859 --> 00:33:15.254
If I go in there and see what...

578
00:33:15.384 --> 00:33:16.777
happened to him.

579
00:33:16.907 --> 00:33:20.520
that is the last image
in my mind.

580
00:33:22.609 --> 00:33:23.871
Forever.

581
00:33:27.701 --> 00:33:29.007
I'll do it. Mom.

582
00:33:29.137 --> 00:33:30.965
No.

583
00:33:31.096 --> 00:33:32.619
No. you won't.

584
00:33:34.621 --> 00:33:35.578
[door opens]

585
00:33:35.709 --> 00:33:39.060
[breathes deeply]

586
00:33:46.676 --> 00:33:49.201
[gloves snapping]

587
00:34:02.344 --> 00:34:04.390
Which is which?

588
00:34:04.520 --> 00:34:06.174
We don't know.

589
00:34:10.396 --> 00:34:11.832
[sniffles]

590
00:34:18.404 --> 00:34:20.058
[sniffles]

591
00:34:22.756 --> 00:34:24.453
[crying]

592
00:34:25.976 --> 00:34:27.761
Paul.

593
00:34:27.891 --> 00:34:29.197
[sniffles]

594
00:34:29.328 --> 00:34:31.330
[bag zips]

595
00:34:44.560 --> 00:34:46.084
[sobs softly]

596
00:34:49.609 --> 00:34:51.001
[sniffles]

597
00:34:55.571 --> 00:34:56.790
[sniffles]

598
00:34:59.967 --> 00:35:01.838
[crying softly]

599
00:35:04.145 --> 00:35:05.755
What's wrong with fingerprints?

600
00:35:05.886 --> 00:35:07.975
How dare you?

601
00:35:08.106 --> 00:35:09.933
[crying]

602
00:35:10.108 --> 00:35:12.110
♪ slow. somber music ♪

603
00:35:20.248 --> 00:35:21.728
[sighs]

604
00:35:21.858 --> 00:35:23.686
Show me what you showed her.

605
00:35:24.687 --> 00:35:26.515
♪ dramatic music ♪

606
00:35:26.646 --> 00:35:28.691
[crying]

607
00:35:38.005 --> 00:35:40.050
♪♪♪

608
00:35:51.366 --> 00:35:52.628
[Liliana over phone]
<i>He had a will?</i>

609
00:35:52.759 --> 00:35:54.456
-Yes.
<i>-Life insurance?</i>

610
00:35:54.587 --> 00:35:56.806
-Yes.
<i>-I hate to ask</i>

611
00:35:56.937 --> 00:35:59.157
 <i>-these things. but--</i>
-We. we're taken care of.

612
00:36:00.158 --> 00:36:01.507
 <i>What about a funeral?</i>

613
00:36:01.637 --> 00:36:03.117
I don't know.

614
00:36:05.337 --> 00:36:08.383
The ranch. maybe.

615
00:36:08.514 --> 00:36:10.516
I guess I'll take care
of his brother as well.

616
00:36:10.646 --> 00:36:12.866
He didn't...
he doesn't have anyone.

617
00:36:12.996 --> 00:36:15.216
 <i>Then you'll never be able</i>
<i>to visit him. Stacy.</i>

618
00:36:15.347 --> 00:36:18.306
I'll close my eyes
when I want to visit him.

619
00:36:18.437 --> 00:36:20.090
 <i>What are you gonna do</i>
<i>with this cabin?</i>

620
00:36:20.221 --> 00:36:22.832
-It's not my cabin.
<i>-It's your cabin now.</i>

621
00:36:22.963 --> 00:36:25.922
 <i>and if you sell it. then</i>
<i>you can't visit him anywhere.</i>

622
00:36:26.053 --> 00:36:27.097
 <i>Think about that.</i>
<i>Bring him home. honey.</i>

623
00:36:27.228 --> 00:36:28.490
Okay. this is too much.

624
00:36:28.621 --> 00:36:29.926
It's too many decisions
for one day.

625
00:36:30.057 --> 00:36:31.841
 <i>-Take a sleeping pill.</i>
-I plan to.

626
00:36:31.972 --> 00:36:33.843
 <i>-I'll call you tomorrow.</i>
-Okay.

627
00:36:33.974 --> 00:36:35.193
[taps phone softly]

628
00:36:40.023 --> 00:36:41.460
[sighs softly]

629
00:36:46.682 --> 00:36:48.510
[sniffles]

630
00:36:58.303 --> 00:37:00.261
-[Stacy crying in distance]
-[TV playing quietly]

631
00:37:08.051 --> 00:37:09.488
[exhales]

632
00:37:10.489 --> 00:37:12.230
[knocking on door]

633
00:37:12.360 --> 00:37:14.014
[gasps softly]

634
00:37:20.194 --> 00:37:22.022
We were thinking
a slumber party.

635
00:37:23.066 --> 00:37:24.067
[softly]
Come on in.

636
00:37:24.198 --> 00:37:25.895
Come on.

637
00:37:26.853 --> 00:37:28.507
[sniffles]

638
00:37:28.637 --> 00:37:29.856
There's bound to be
some shitty pizza in this town.

639
00:37:29.986 --> 00:37:31.336
[exhales]
You think?

640
00:37:31.466 --> 00:37:33.120
[Abigail laughs]
I hope so.

641
00:37:35.122 --> 00:37:36.384
[exhales]

642
00:37:37.385 --> 00:37:40.432
Girls. can you ninja up
some Netflix on the TV?

643
00:37:41.476 --> 00:37:42.695
For you.

644
00:37:42.825 --> 00:37:45.045
[Stacy]
Oh. God bless you.

645
00:37:45.175 --> 00:37:47.526
[Abigail chuckles] Nothing
teaches you to self-medicate

646
00:37:47.656 --> 00:37:49.702
like a good divorce.

647
00:37:50.746 --> 00:37:51.965
What do you want. Grandma?

648
00:37:52.095 --> 00:37:53.619
A comedy.

649
00:37:53.749 --> 00:37:55.490
Uh...

650
00:37:55.621 --> 00:37:58.537
Hmm. how about
<i>A River Runs Through It?</i>

651
00:37:58.667 --> 00:38:00.843
It was Grandpa's favorite movie.

652
00:38:00.974 --> 00:38:02.628
[knock on door]

653
00:38:02.758 --> 00:38:04.151
A river may run through it.

654
00:38:04.282 --> 00:38:06.545
but I've never actually
gotten through it.

655
00:38:06.675 --> 00:38:10.592
-[laughs softly]
-So. in honor of him.

656
00:38:12.377 --> 00:38:14.422
You've come to the right place.

657
00:38:16.337 --> 00:38:18.774
Uh... Pizza. Can you find some?

658
00:38:18.905 --> 00:38:20.036
-Pizza?
-Yeah.

659
00:38:20.167 --> 00:38:21.821
-Yeah. I'll--
-And ice cream.

660
00:38:21.951 --> 00:38:23.083
Uh. what flavors?

661
00:38:23.213 --> 00:38:24.563
[Abigail]
Dazzle us with options.

662
00:38:24.693 --> 00:38:26.826
-[Russell] Done.
-Thanks. Russ.

663
00:38:28.131 --> 00:38:29.307
[door closes]

664
00:38:29.437 --> 00:38:31.657
Is it gonna be sad?

665
00:38:31.787 --> 00:38:33.267
Oh...

666
00:38:33.398 --> 00:38:36.314
It's about fishing.
How sad can it be?

667
00:38:38.490 --> 00:38:40.448
-[string music playing over TV]
-[sniffling]

668
00:38:47.847 --> 00:38:50.197
[Older Norman]
<i>I am haunted by waters.</i>

669
00:38:51.546 --> 00:38:53.809
[Abigail crying] Thanks. Mom.
I sure feel better now.

670
00:38:53.940 --> 00:38:55.637
[chuckles] Jesus.

671
00:38:55.768 --> 00:38:57.900
It made your father cry. too.

672
00:38:58.031 --> 00:39:01.034
-[exhales]
-Every time. like a big baby.

673
00:39:01.164 --> 00:39:02.644
[chuckles]

674
00:39:03.645 --> 00:39:06.213
[whispering]
Uh. that and. uh. <i>Rudy.</i>

675
00:39:06.344 --> 00:39:10.043
Only men can cry
over fishing and football.

676
00:39:10.173 --> 00:39:12.654
God. for life to be that simple.

677
00:39:12.785 --> 00:39:14.308
[sighs]

678
00:39:14.439 --> 00:39:16.528
-[sniffles]
-You know.

679
00:39:16.658 --> 00:39:19.792
in 39 years of marriage...

680
00:39:19.922 --> 00:39:21.446
we never fought.

681
00:39:22.447 --> 00:39:23.665
Not once.

682
00:39:24.710 --> 00:39:27.930
I mean. we... we-we danced

683
00:39:28.061 --> 00:39:29.715
-right to the edge. but...
-[laughing]

684
00:39:29.845 --> 00:39:33.240
But we both knew
how-how precious

685
00:39:33.371 --> 00:39:36.548
and how rare what we had was.

686
00:39:36.678 --> 00:39:38.114
[breath trembles]

687
00:39:40.203 --> 00:39:45.034
I should be happy
that he died out here...

688
00:39:45.165 --> 00:39:48.081
doing something
that he loves. not...

689
00:39:49.648 --> 00:39:51.824
...tethered
to some hospital bed.

690
00:39:51.954 --> 00:39:55.436
like most men waiting to die.

691
00:39:55.567 --> 00:39:57.003
[exhales]

692
00:39:58.526 --> 00:40:03.531
He died living. not existing.

693
00:40:05.403 --> 00:40:07.448
How many could say that?

694
00:40:08.536 --> 00:40:10.582
I hope you find
what we had someday. honey.

695
00:40:10.712 --> 00:40:12.192
I really. really do.

696
00:40:12.322 --> 00:40:15.064
I hope you meet a man
that's worth missing.

697
00:40:15.238 --> 00:40:17.806
♪ slow. gentle music ♪

698
00:40:17.937 --> 00:40:19.634
I'd just like one
to return my calls.

699
00:40:19.765 --> 00:40:21.288
-Oh. God.
-[laughs]

700
00:40:21.419 --> 00:40:23.421
We got to work
on your standards.

701
00:40:25.161 --> 00:40:26.598
[exhales]

702
00:40:28.687 --> 00:40:30.558
♪ slow. majestic music ♪

703
00:40:30.689 --> 00:40:32.691
[birds chirping]

704
00:40:50.491 --> 00:40:52.362
Do you guys have service?

705
00:40:54.930 --> 00:40:56.149
Are we close?

706
00:40:57.237 --> 00:40:59.021
I don't know.
Never been there before.

707
00:40:59.152 --> 00:41:01.328
We're close. I think.

708
00:41:16.822 --> 00:41:18.301
I guess this is it.

709
00:41:18.432 --> 00:41:19.694
This is it?

710
00:41:19.825 --> 00:41:21.304
This is what the nav says.

711
00:41:21.435 --> 00:41:22.871
Stop.

712
00:41:41.977 --> 00:41:43.675
I've seen that photo.

713
00:41:46.373 --> 00:41:47.940
Okay.

714
00:41:48.114 --> 00:41:50.159
♪♪♪

715
00:42:19.928 --> 00:42:21.930
♪♪♪

716
00:42:34.073 --> 00:42:36.423
Should we be worried
about bears?

717
00:42:36.554 --> 00:42:39.034
Preston never mentioned bears.

718
00:42:49.001 --> 00:42:51.003
[door creaking]

719
00:43:15.201 --> 00:43:16.594
[door closes]

720
00:43:25.951 --> 00:43:27.387
[Abigail sighs]

721
00:43:31.434 --> 00:43:32.479
[door closes in distance]

722
00:43:32.610 --> 00:43:34.612
[Paige]
It's very weird.

723
00:43:34.742 --> 00:43:37.397
There's a sink and a shower
but no toilet.

724
00:43:37.527 --> 00:43:39.094
Toilets are outside.

725
00:43:39.225 --> 00:43:41.270
-Outside?
-There's no septic system.

726
00:43:41.401 --> 00:43:44.012
The cabins are too close
to the river.

727
00:43:44.143 --> 00:43:45.840
-That's why we never visited.
-[Russell] I have

728
00:43:45.971 --> 00:43:49.365
absolutely no idea how you would
get this furniture up here.

729
00:43:53.543 --> 00:43:55.067
Where are you going?

730
00:43:55.197 --> 00:43:56.721
I want to find Preston's cabin.

731
00:43:56.851 --> 00:43:58.505
Well. take this. Be careful.

732
00:44:00.812 --> 00:44:01.987
[Russell]
Uh. what's that?

733
00:44:02.117 --> 00:44:04.467
-Bear spray.
-You said no bears.

734
00:44:04.598 --> 00:44:05.991
I said he never mentioned bears.

735
00:44:06.165 --> 00:44:07.949
♪ slow. majestic music ♪

736
00:44:08.994 --> 00:44:09.995
[door closes]

737
00:44:12.606 --> 00:44:14.652
[birds chirping]

738
00:44:24.618 --> 00:44:26.664
♪♪♪

739
00:44:50.383 --> 00:44:52.428
[door creaking]

740
00:44:59.044 --> 00:45:00.262
[door closes]

741
00:45:09.228 --> 00:45:11.230
♪♪♪

742
00:45:32.120 --> 00:45:34.122
[screams]

743
00:45:35.994 --> 00:45:37.996
♪♪♪

744
00:45:54.447 --> 00:45:55.970
[Stacy]
I'm taking a bath.

745
00:45:56.101 --> 00:45:57.145
[Preston over phone]
<i>Don't you have dinner</i>

746
00:45:57.276 --> 00:45:58.320
 <i>with the girls tonight?</i>

747
00:45:58.451 --> 00:45:59.974
No. um...

748
00:46:00.105 --> 00:46:02.716
Bridgett has some dance.

749
00:46:02.847 --> 00:46:05.153
something in Chelsea
of all places.

750
00:46:05.284 --> 00:46:08.417
As if there aren't
12 ballet academies nearby.

751
00:46:08.548 --> 00:46:11.507
And Paige has some work.

752
00:46:11.638 --> 00:46:13.683
something with Russell
at that... [sighs]

753
00:46:13.814 --> 00:46:15.990
...that new club
they wasted their money joining.

754
00:46:16.121 --> 00:46:17.557
[grunts softly]
Our money.

755
00:46:18.645 --> 00:46:21.169
They wasted our money
joining it.

756
00:46:21.300 --> 00:46:23.519
 <i>I stand corrected.</i>

757
00:46:23.650 --> 00:46:24.694
 <i>What are you doing?</i>

758
00:46:24.825 --> 00:46:27.262
I am making coffee.

759
00:46:27.393 --> 00:46:29.003
What time is it there?

760
00:46:29.134 --> 00:46:30.657
 <i>I don't know. Five-thirty?</i>

761
00:46:30.788 --> 00:46:33.051
Babe. you'll be up all night.

762
00:46:33.181 --> 00:46:36.968
Well. I try to sleep as little
as possible when I'm here.

763
00:46:38.012 --> 00:46:40.101
You know. at night. the bull elk

764
00:46:40.232 --> 00:46:42.364
come down to the river
and bugle.

765
00:46:42.495 --> 00:46:44.584
-[laughs] They bugle?
<i>-They bugle.</i>

766
00:46:44.714 --> 00:46:47.108
 <i>Kind of a high-pitched.</i>
<i>almost like a whistle.</i>

767
00:46:47.239 --> 00:46:49.110
 <i>and it drives</i>
<i>the lady elk crazy.</i>

768
00:46:49.241 --> 00:46:50.677
Oh.

769
00:46:50.808 --> 00:46:53.419
I remember
when you used to bugle.

770
00:46:53.549 --> 00:46:55.029
[chuckles]
I can still bugle.

771
00:46:55.160 --> 00:46:56.639
 <i>Well...</i>

772
00:46:56.770 --> 00:46:58.728
 <i>it's more like a trombone</i>
<i>these days.</i>

773
00:46:58.859 --> 00:47:02.515
 <i>but hey.</i>
<i>I am no spring lady elk.</i>

774
00:47:02.645 --> 00:47:04.734
 <i>so trombone</i>
<i>is just fine with me.</i>

775
00:47:04.865 --> 00:47:06.388
How do you make coffee?

776
00:47:06.519 --> 00:47:08.303
I-I thought you said
you didn't have electricity.

777
00:47:08.434 --> 00:47:10.740
 <i>Well. there's electricity.</i>
<i>just no outlets.</i>

778
00:47:10.871 --> 00:47:13.656
You know. we got a light
over the porch

779
00:47:13.787 --> 00:47:15.702
and light over the table.

780
00:47:15.833 --> 00:47:17.182
 <i>Huh.</i>

781
00:47:17.312 --> 00:47:19.184
 <i>You didn't answer my question.</i>

782
00:47:19.314 --> 00:47:22.274
Well. I build a fire
in the stove

783
00:47:22.404 --> 00:47:25.320
and fill the pot from the river.

784
00:47:25.451 --> 00:47:28.062
 <i>Pour the coffee in the pot.</i>

785
00:47:28.193 --> 00:47:29.759
 <i>boil the water.</i>
<i>and there you go.</i>

786
00:47:29.934 --> 00:47:31.239
♪ slow. gentle music ♪

787
00:47:31.370 --> 00:47:33.198
You can taste the smoke. Stacy.

788
00:47:33.328 --> 00:47:37.332
It's the best cup of coffee
you'll ever have.

789
00:47:37.463 --> 00:47:39.857
[laughs]
<i>Oh. my God.</i>

790
00:47:39.987 --> 00:47:42.250
Oh. honey. I think
you are romanticizing this

791
00:47:42.381 --> 00:47:45.645
to the point
of physical impossibility.

792
00:47:45.775 --> 00:47:48.169
 <i>Maybe you should</i>
<i>just wash the pot.</i>

793
00:47:48.300 --> 00:47:50.041
Well. technically.
it's a percolator.

794
00:47:50.171 --> 00:47:52.957
 <i>-Ah.</i>
-And if you'll ever come here.

795
00:47:53.087 --> 00:47:55.263
I'll make you a cup.

796
00:47:55.394 --> 00:47:57.048
The best you'll ever have.

797
00:47:57.178 --> 00:47:58.876
 <i>If you really wanted me</i>
<i>to come there.</i>

798
00:47:59.006 --> 00:48:00.747
you and your brother
would build a bathroom.

799
00:48:00.878 --> 00:48:02.357
 <i>It has a bathroom.</i>

800
00:48:02.488 --> 00:48:04.098
Inside the house.

801
00:48:04.229 --> 00:48:06.884
[laughs]
<i>God. you're spoiled.</i>

802
00:48:07.014 --> 00:48:09.190
The conveniences have
become your necessities.

803
00:48:09.321 --> 00:48:12.802
[laughs] <i>We went camping once</i>
<i>a long time ago.</i>

804
00:48:12.933 --> 00:48:14.935
 <i>or have you managed</i>
<i>to block that out?</i>

805
00:48:15.066 --> 00:48:17.677
[chuckles] No. no. no. no.
That was not camping.

806
00:48:17.807 --> 00:48:19.592
That was an excuse
to get you in a tent.

807
00:48:19.722 --> 00:48:20.767
I had planned nothing

808
00:48:20.898 --> 00:48:22.377
 <i>past the sex.</i>

809
00:48:22.508 --> 00:48:24.031
[laughs]

810
00:48:24.162 --> 00:48:27.426
Well. you married
a city mouse. honey.

811
00:48:27.556 --> 00:48:30.037
City mice stay in the city.

812
00:48:31.125 --> 00:48:33.475
 <i>You need to see it. Stace.</i>

813
00:48:34.476 --> 00:48:35.738
 <i>Just once.</i>

814
00:48:35.869 --> 00:48:37.610
I do. I do see it.

815
00:48:37.740 --> 00:48:39.046
Every time you send
a picture of you

816
00:48:39.177 --> 00:48:40.961
and some traumatized trout.

817
00:48:41.962 --> 00:48:44.399
 <i>Nah. it's not the same.</i>

818
00:48:44.530 --> 00:48:46.184
Oh.

819
00:48:49.187 --> 00:48:51.189
[crying]

820
00:48:54.235 --> 00:48:56.237
[panting]

821
00:49:18.129 --> 00:49:19.347
Girls?

822
00:49:21.045 --> 00:49:22.960
Girls?

823
00:49:24.700 --> 00:49:26.528
Where are you going?

824
00:49:26.659 --> 00:49:28.443
-We just want to check it out.
-Well. don't climb on anything.

825
00:49:28.574 --> 00:49:30.141
Watch out for snakes.

826
00:49:30.271 --> 00:49:31.751
-Are there snakes?
-I don't know.

827
00:49:31.881 --> 00:49:33.405
so you probably
should watch out for them.

828
00:49:46.722 --> 00:49:48.376
What in the world?

829
00:49:48.507 --> 00:49:50.944
-[door opens. closes]
-[Russell] Uh. I found a motel

830
00:49:51.075 --> 00:49:52.946
about an hour away.

831
00:49:53.077 --> 00:49:54.774
Does not look great.

832
00:49:54.904 --> 00:49:56.689
We could drive
into Bozeman or Helena.

833
00:49:56.819 --> 00:50:00.693
Everything seems to be about
two hours from everything else.

834
00:50:05.524 --> 00:50:06.873
How long you think
she wants to stay?

835
00:50:07.004 --> 00:50:08.788
Gonna go find out.

836
00:50:10.659 --> 00:50:12.096
[sighs]

837
00:50:15.447 --> 00:50:16.535
[Abigail]
Mom?

838
00:50:16.665 --> 00:50:18.667
[liquid bubbling softly]

839
00:50:19.668 --> 00:50:21.105
Mom?

840
00:50:23.716 --> 00:50:24.978
What's that?

841
00:50:27.937 --> 00:50:29.156
Coffee maker.

842
00:50:30.462 --> 00:50:33.334
-It is?
-Think it's done.

843
00:50:33.465 --> 00:50:35.075
You want some?

844
00:50:35.206 --> 00:50:36.642
Why not?

845
00:50:37.817 --> 00:50:39.819
[soft clatter]

846
00:50:48.567 --> 00:50:50.482
[sighs]

847
00:50:54.312 --> 00:50:55.965
He sat here and called me.

848
00:50:57.967 --> 00:50:59.404
Right here.

849
00:51:02.798 --> 00:51:05.279
Talked about fish.

850
00:51:05.410 --> 00:51:06.498
[chuckles softly]

851
00:51:06.628 --> 00:51:09.196
And I'd pretend like I cared.

852
00:51:11.981 --> 00:51:13.635
He was right.

853
00:51:15.202 --> 00:51:17.422
Not the same in pictures.

854
00:51:20.033 --> 00:51:23.341
I never came with him because...

855
00:51:24.733 --> 00:51:26.561
...I thought I'd be bored.

856
00:51:28.041 --> 00:51:29.521
Or. uh. you know. a third wheel.

857
00:51:29.651 --> 00:51:31.784
I didn't want
to interrupt his man time.

858
00:51:31.914 --> 00:51:33.133
his brother time.

859
00:51:35.179 --> 00:51:36.832
[sighs]

860
00:51:36.963 --> 00:51:38.965
I thought about bringing you two
out when you were younger.

861
00:51:39.096 --> 00:51:41.968
But then. you know.
it's not a vacation for him.

862
00:51:42.099 --> 00:51:44.057
It's a. it's a trip.

863
00:51:44.188 --> 00:51:48.583
and he's worried about pleasing
you and not himself. and...

864
00:51:49.976 --> 00:51:52.021
Wow. was I wrong.

865
00:51:54.111 --> 00:51:57.288
I robbed us of this.

866
00:51:57.375 --> 00:52:00.552
I robbed him
of sharing it with us.

867
00:52:00.682 --> 00:52:02.423
Please don't do that.

868
00:52:03.424 --> 00:52:06.123
Do not blame yourself
for things that you didn't do.

869
00:52:06.297 --> 00:52:07.907
♪ gentle music ♪

870
00:52:08.037 --> 00:52:12.912
You had a loving marriage
for 40 years in New York City.

871
00:52:13.042 --> 00:52:16.089
I mean. they should build
a statue of you two.

872
00:52:16.220 --> 00:52:18.222
[laughing]

873
00:52:20.354 --> 00:52:21.573
Miss him.

874
00:52:22.574 --> 00:52:24.402
God knows I will.

875
00:52:25.533 --> 00:52:27.840
But no blame.

876
00:52:27.970 --> 00:52:30.190
You two did it right.

877
00:52:34.063 --> 00:52:35.891
It's getting late.

878
00:52:36.022 --> 00:52:38.285
Motel's a hike.
We can come back in the morning.

879
00:52:39.808 --> 00:52:41.245
Mm...

880
00:52:42.768 --> 00:52:44.378
I'm gonna stay here.

881
00:52:45.988 --> 00:52:48.339
Mmm. He was right.

882
00:52:48.469 --> 00:52:50.471
You can taste the smoke.

883
00:52:52.865 --> 00:52:54.127
Hmm.

884
00:52:56.825 --> 00:52:58.871
♪♪♪

885
00:53:08.707 --> 00:53:10.230
[Paige]
<i>She's just gonna stay?</i>

886
00:53:10.361 --> 00:53:12.754
And do what? There's not
even a bathroom here.

887
00:53:12.885 --> 00:53:15.583
Oh. I found one.
They're... It's outside.

888
00:53:15.714 --> 00:53:17.194
It's Spartan.

889
00:53:17.324 --> 00:53:18.934
What does "Spartan" mean?

890
00:53:19.065 --> 00:53:20.980
-Rustic.
-[Russell] Yeah.

891
00:53:21.110 --> 00:53:24.462
There's. like. a hornet's nest
inside the hole.

892
00:53:24.592 --> 00:53:26.072
Adds a certain degree
of difficulty.

893
00:53:26.203 --> 00:53:28.161
She can't stay here.

894
00:53:28.292 --> 00:53:29.989
Okay? It's selfish.

895
00:53:30.119 --> 00:53:32.861
She's acting like she's
the only one who lost somebody.

896
00:53:32.992 --> 00:53:36.169
-He was my father.
-Don't you fucking dare.

897
00:53:36.300 --> 00:53:39.346
She has been with him
since she was 19.

898
00:53:39.477 --> 00:53:41.783
I've been with him
since I was born. So were you!

899
00:53:41.914 --> 00:53:43.220
We were not with him!

900
00:53:43.350 --> 00:53:46.353
He was present
when we needed something.

901
00:53:46.484 --> 00:53:49.443
When we needed a chauffeur
or a cheerleader.

902
00:53:49.574 --> 00:53:52.968
A therapist. A bank.

903
00:53:53.099 --> 00:53:54.753
You want to mourn something?
Why don't we mourn the time

904
00:53:54.883 --> 00:53:56.320
that we didn't give him?

905
00:53:56.450 --> 00:53:59.758
He was her lover
and her best friend.

906
00:53:59.888 --> 00:54:01.673
It is not the same thing.

907
00:54:01.803 --> 00:54:03.849
You lost the idea of him. Paige.

908
00:54:03.979 --> 00:54:05.807
-which you can still have.
-[door opens]

909
00:54:05.938 --> 00:54:08.332
-Girls. go back outside now.
-We can hear you yelling.

910
00:54:08.462 --> 00:54:10.203
[door opens]

911
00:54:30.136 --> 00:54:31.442
[freezer door closes]

912
00:54:33.531 --> 00:54:34.619
[Stacy]
Oh!

913
00:54:34.749 --> 00:54:37.230
God bless your uncle.

914
00:54:38.275 --> 00:54:41.626
Hey. did I see. uh.
a garden somewhere?

915
00:54:41.756 --> 00:54:43.149
Mm-hmm. by the barn.

916
00:54:43.280 --> 00:54:45.499
-What's in it?
-We didn't check.

917
00:54:45.630 --> 00:54:47.936
-Let's check.
-Mm-hmm.

918
00:54:51.897 --> 00:54:53.115
[tongue clicks]

919
00:54:54.639 --> 00:54:58.512
I'd say you nailed it. with me.

920
00:54:59.557 --> 00:55:03.300
But if that's all he was
to you two...

921
00:55:05.084 --> 00:55:06.912
...what a shame. girls.

922
00:55:12.091 --> 00:55:13.832
[door closes]

923
00:55:14.006 --> 00:55:16.617
♪ slow. somber music ♪

924
00:55:16.748 --> 00:55:19.228
Kale and. I think. Swiss chard.

925
00:55:19.359 --> 00:55:21.143
I think these are scallions.
[gasps]

926
00:55:21.274 --> 00:55:23.276
Oh. this is thyme.

927
00:55:23.407 --> 00:55:26.975
This... will come in handy.

928
00:55:27.106 --> 00:55:28.194
Nice. right?

929
00:55:28.325 --> 00:55:30.588
[gasps]
Strawberries?

930
00:55:30.718 --> 00:55:32.416
-Wow.
-[Macy] Wait.

931
00:55:32.546 --> 00:55:34.548
You can just grow them?

932
00:55:34.679 --> 00:55:35.854
Apparently.

933
00:55:35.984 --> 00:55:37.812
I thought they just came
from farms.

934
00:55:37.943 --> 00:55:41.033
Well. that's what this is.
It's an itty-bitty farm.

935
00:55:41.163 --> 00:55:43.470
-Oh.
-I think...

936
00:55:43.601 --> 00:55:45.124
this is spinach.

937
00:55:45.254 --> 00:55:47.169
What's this?

938
00:55:48.649 --> 00:55:50.172
[Stacy]
Oh. shit!

939
00:55:50.303 --> 00:55:51.304
-That's a snake!
-[girls screaming]

940
00:55:51.435 --> 00:55:53.393
Everything okay?!

941
00:55:53.524 --> 00:55:55.177
[Stacy]
We're okay! It's okay.

942
00:55:55.308 --> 00:55:57.223
He's more scared of you
than you are of him.

943
00:55:57.354 --> 00:56:00.226
Okay. let's just go over here.

944
00:56:00.400 --> 00:56:02.968
♪ slow. dramatic music ♪

945
00:56:03.098 --> 00:56:04.796
[sniffs. clears throat]

946
00:56:18.287 --> 00:56:19.463
Oh!

947
00:56:21.987 --> 00:56:23.467
All right.

948
00:56:24.468 --> 00:56:28.297
Lesson learned.
Less is more with this stuff.

949
00:56:30.561 --> 00:56:31.779
Ooh.

950
00:56:39.352 --> 00:56:40.919
[chuckles softly]

951
00:56:41.049 --> 00:56:43.443
When was the last time
you saw one of those. girls?

952
00:56:43.574 --> 00:56:45.010
One of what?

953
00:56:45.967 --> 00:56:47.229
Sunset.

954
00:56:49.667 --> 00:56:50.885
Can't remember?

955
00:56:51.886 --> 00:56:53.366
Nah. me neither.

956
00:56:56.674 --> 00:56:58.806
[Abigail] There must be a nice
grocery store around here.

957
00:56:58.937 --> 00:57:01.026
because Paul has every cheese
on the planet.

958
00:57:01.156 --> 00:57:03.245
I sent a package.
Your father likes to rough it.

959
00:57:03.376 --> 00:57:05.422
but he doesn't like to starve.

960
00:57:05.552 --> 00:57:08.555
-Somebody grate the Parmesan?
-Uh. we got it here.

961
00:57:08.686 --> 00:57:10.731
[gentle music playing
over speakers]

962
00:57:14.605 --> 00:57:15.910
[Bridgett]
What are you making?

963
00:57:16.041 --> 00:57:17.434
Polenta.

964
00:57:17.564 --> 00:57:19.131
How are you making polenta?

965
00:57:19.261 --> 00:57:21.307
You just boil cornmeal. honey.

966
00:57:21.438 --> 00:57:24.223
I-I don't think polenta
has corn in it.

967
00:57:24.353 --> 00:57:26.268
That's all polenta has.

968
00:57:26.399 --> 00:57:28.836
Just corn and liquid and cheese.

969
00:57:28.967 --> 00:57:30.795
-I think that's grits.
-Yes.

970
00:57:30.925 --> 00:57:33.101
Grits and polenta
are the same thing.

971
00:57:33.232 --> 00:57:36.191
Mother. they make grits
in Alabama.

972
00:57:36.322 --> 00:57:39.238
You're telling me it's the same
thing as the dish from Italy?

973
00:57:39.368 --> 00:57:40.587
It's the exact same thing.

974
00:57:40.718 --> 00:57:43.242
Just finish it
with different toppings.

975
00:57:43.372 --> 00:57:45.200
If it has different ingredients.
it's a different dish.

976
00:57:45.331 --> 00:57:47.289
-Can somebody pour me some wine?
-[scoffs] Like.

977
00:57:47.420 --> 00:57:48.421
they're making the same thing
in Birmingham

978
00:57:48.552 --> 00:57:50.336
that they're making in Florence?

979
00:57:50.467 --> 00:57:53.252
With different cheese.
That's the only difference.

980
00:57:53.382 --> 00:57:55.428
Okay. I'm not
gonna argue with you

981
00:57:55.559 --> 00:57:57.778
because you're in mourning.
but the time will come

982
00:57:57.909 --> 00:57:59.519
where I will tell you
how wrong you are.

983
00:57:59.650 --> 00:58:01.521
[door closes]

984
00:58:03.044 --> 00:58:04.481
[Russell clears throat]

985
00:58:05.917 --> 00:58:07.527
Um...

986
00:58:07.658 --> 00:58:09.486
[Stacy]
Oh. that looks great.

987
00:58:09.616 --> 00:58:11.270
Yeah. um...

988
00:58:11.400 --> 00:58:13.533
[whispers]
I don't think this is beef.

989
00:58:14.665 --> 00:58:16.318
-What? It's beef.
-Yeah. it didn't.

990
00:58:16.449 --> 00:58:18.190
it didn't cook like beef.
it doesn't smell like beef.

991
00:58:18.320 --> 00:58:21.062
Look at me. It's beef. okay?

992
00:58:21.193 --> 00:58:23.412
[whispers]
For tonight. it's beef.

993
00:58:24.413 --> 00:58:25.937
Okay.

994
00:58:26.067 --> 00:58:29.723
Um. but w-what-what...
what is it really?

995
00:58:30.768 --> 00:58:32.421
It said "elk."

996
00:58:32.552 --> 00:58:34.467
but the world
doesn't need to know that.

997
00:58:34.598 --> 00:58:36.425
Why?

998
00:58:36.556 --> 00:58:39.603
Do you think the. uh. you think
the world would. uh. r-revolt?

999
00:58:39.733 --> 00:58:41.822
How do you think
your wife would react?

1000
00:58:41.953 --> 00:58:43.650
[laughs softly]
Um. yeah.

1001
00:58:43.781 --> 00:58:45.696
not. uh. not good?

1002
00:58:45.826 --> 00:58:47.436
-Multiply that by four.
-Right.

1003
00:58:47.567 --> 00:58:49.482
Okay. so. should I slice it?

1004
00:58:49.613 --> 00:58:52.180
No. I think you should just do
whatever you think will make it

1005
00:58:52.311 --> 00:58:53.355
-look more like beef.
-Okay. Yeah. yeah. Yeah.

1006
00:58:53.486 --> 00:58:54.922
I got it. Got it.

1007
00:58:57.142 --> 00:58:58.665
[Bridgett]
Can I have more of the steak?

1008
00:58:58.796 --> 00:59:00.667
[Stacy]
Mm. You bet. honey.

1009
00:59:00.798 --> 00:59:03.627
Me. too. please.
You're a really good cook.

1010
00:59:03.757 --> 00:59:06.368
-Thanks.
-Steak's really good. honey.

1011
00:59:10.242 --> 00:59:11.939
Thank you.

1012
00:59:12.070 --> 00:59:13.898
-Do you girls want more grits?
-[Stacy] It's not grits.

1013
00:59:14.028 --> 00:59:15.726
-It's polenta.
-All right. you and I

1014
00:59:15.856 --> 00:59:18.380
can agree to disagree. but
I'm not lying to my children.

1015
00:59:18.511 --> 00:59:21.035
-They're my children.
-They're my nieces.

1016
00:59:21.166 --> 00:59:22.907
You know what I mean.
They're basically my children.

1017
00:59:23.037 --> 00:59:25.039
They're not even
kind of your children.

1018
00:59:25.170 --> 00:59:27.694
but if you want them
to be your children.

1019
00:59:27.825 --> 00:59:30.001
you can get them to dance
on Tuesday and Thursday

1020
00:59:30.131 --> 00:59:31.568
and then take them
to fucking Paramus

1021
00:59:31.698 --> 00:59:33.047
at eight in the morning
for gymnastics.

1022
00:59:33.178 --> 00:59:34.658
-[laughs softly]
-Fine.

1023
00:59:34.788 --> 00:59:37.182
"The children."
I'm not lying to the children.

1024
00:59:37.312 --> 00:59:39.184
I don't see why not.
I'm lying to mine.

1025
00:59:40.402 --> 00:59:43.580
Are you enjoying the elk. Paige?

1026
00:59:43.710 --> 00:59:45.451
The what?

1027
00:59:45.582 --> 00:59:47.148
It's elk.

1028
00:59:47.279 --> 00:59:48.715
[spits quietly]

1029
00:59:52.371 --> 00:59:54.503
Elk? Like the deer?

1030
00:59:54.634 --> 00:59:56.070
No. no. not a deer.

1031
00:59:56.201 --> 00:59:57.376
-The big deer?
-No. it's a different species.

1032
00:59:57.506 --> 01:00:00.466
It's kind of like
grits and polenta.

1033
01:00:00.597 --> 01:00:03.077
-according to your logic.
-It has big horns

1034
01:00:03.208 --> 01:00:05.993
and hooves.
and it was roaming around freely

1035
01:00:06.124 --> 01:00:07.516
until your brother-in-law
shot it.

1036
01:00:07.647 --> 01:00:08.866
That's what I'm eating?

1037
01:00:08.996 --> 01:00:10.824
I'm not sure
that they have hooves.

1038
01:00:10.955 --> 01:00:12.565
Did you know?

1039
01:00:12.696 --> 01:00:15.568
-[stammers. chuckles]
-You knew. I can fucking tell.

1040
01:00:15.699 --> 01:00:17.004
You knew. and you cooked it.

1041
01:00:17.135 --> 01:00:18.397
and you were just gonna
let me eat it?

1042
01:00:18.527 --> 01:00:19.528
I think it's really good.

1043
01:00:21.008 --> 01:00:22.749
-Mom.
-[Stacy] What do you think

1044
01:00:22.880 --> 01:00:25.404
is gonna happen to all the food
in this house. Paige?

1045
01:00:25.534 --> 01:00:28.276
It's gonna get eaten
or it's gonna rot.

1046
01:00:28.407 --> 01:00:29.669
I didn't kill the thing.

1047
01:00:29.800 --> 01:00:31.279
Your uncle will never
kill another one.

1048
01:00:31.410 --> 01:00:33.151
I suppose we could
throw it all away.

1049
01:00:33.281 --> 01:00:35.457
And then it's nourishing

1050
01:00:35.588 --> 01:00:39.287
some raccoon or worms or...
I guess.

1051
01:00:39.418 --> 01:00:41.594
Or it can nourish us.

1052
01:00:41.725 --> 01:00:44.205
Which is what it's doing.

1053
01:00:45.250 --> 01:00:46.904
When's the last time
you cooked a meal. Paige?

1054
01:00:47.034 --> 01:00:49.733
Not reheated one.
not microwaved one.

1055
01:00:49.863 --> 01:00:51.473
We picked that from a garden.

1056
01:00:51.604 --> 01:00:54.085
Your uncle took that
from somewhere around here.

1057
01:00:54.215 --> 01:00:56.740
The cornmeal is in a jar.

1058
01:00:56.870 --> 01:00:58.437
Did he make that? Maybe.

1059
01:00:58.567 --> 01:01:01.832
Everything we ate
came from this...

1060
01:01:01.962 --> 01:01:05.966
this little world
that your father adored.

1061
01:01:06.097 --> 01:01:09.883
We made a meal
from this place together.

1062
01:01:10.014 --> 01:01:12.146
I think it's beautiful.

1063
01:01:12.277 --> 01:01:14.061
I think it's perfect.

1064
01:01:14.192 --> 01:01:16.020
And I know
your father would. too.

1065
01:01:16.194 --> 01:01:18.239
♪ slow. somber music ♪

1066
01:01:19.327 --> 01:01:22.113
I wonder who has to die for us
to make another meal together.

1067
01:01:22.243 --> 01:01:23.462
[chuckles]

1068
01:01:25.856 --> 01:01:27.640
Ah. so-- Good night.

1069
01:01:33.167 --> 01:01:34.386
[sniffles]

1070
01:01:45.179 --> 01:01:47.181
♪♪♪

1071
01:02:13.599 --> 01:02:16.167
I wonder if that stuff works.

1072
01:02:17.603 --> 01:02:18.909
I guess.

1073
01:02:19.039 --> 01:02:21.085
So long as the wind
is at your back.

1074
01:02:21.215 --> 01:02:23.217
[chuckles]
Good point.

1075
01:02:26.830 --> 01:02:28.875
What are you reading?

1076
01:02:30.137 --> 01:02:31.748
A journal.

1077
01:02:33.706 --> 01:02:36.100
Your father kept a journal here.

1078
01:02:38.145 --> 01:02:40.104
Twenty-five years.

1079
01:02:40.234 --> 01:02:42.410
Uh. what's it say?

1080
01:02:42.541 --> 01:02:46.850
Talks about. um. which river.

1081
01:02:46.980 --> 01:02:49.896
and then it says
to crack a window

1082
01:02:50.027 --> 01:02:51.637
when lighting the stove
in a wind.

1083
01:02:51.768 --> 01:02:54.771
Uh. there's a downdraft
that pushes the smoke

1084
01:02:54.901 --> 01:02:56.511
back into the cabin.

1085
01:02:56.642 --> 01:03:00.472
It's half diary. half...

1086
01:03:00.602 --> 01:03:02.039
how-to guide.

1087
01:03:04.041 --> 01:03:05.564
Then there's this...

1088
01:03:07.914 --> 01:03:09.350
...about me.

1089
01:03:10.699 --> 01:03:15.530
There's a. um. spot upriver...

1090
01:03:18.055 --> 01:03:20.709
...and he calls it
Stacy's Valley.

1091
01:03:20.840 --> 01:03:23.016
The elk don't graze there
for some reason.

1092
01:03:23.147 --> 01:03:26.280
so the grass grows tall
and it's yellow.

1093
01:03:26.411 --> 01:03:29.022
and it reminds him of my hair.

1094
01:03:30.589 --> 01:03:32.634
[sighs]

1095
01:03:37.378 --> 01:03:39.772
I-I need to know...

1096
01:03:39.903 --> 01:03:41.208
[exhales]

1097
01:03:41.339 --> 01:03:43.341
...his last little secret.

1098
01:03:45.734 --> 01:03:49.651
How can I say goodbye
when there's still...

1099
01:03:50.914 --> 01:03:52.785
...more to know?

1100
01:03:59.444 --> 01:04:01.620
So. tomorrow morning.

1101
01:04:01.750 --> 01:04:03.927
I'm gonna get up...

1102
01:04:04.928 --> 01:04:08.540
...and I'm gonna find
this little valley.

1103
01:04:17.549 --> 01:04:19.943
And then I'm gonna bring
your father here.

1104
01:04:22.554 --> 01:04:24.556
And I'm gonna bury him there.

1105
01:04:26.340 --> 01:04:28.038
And then I'm gonna
take this book.

1106
01:04:28.168 --> 01:04:29.866
and I'm gonna visit

1107
01:04:29.996 --> 01:04:33.870
every place he wrote about.

1108
01:04:35.959 --> 01:04:39.440
And you can tell me I'm crazy.
you can say I need to move on.

1109
01:04:39.571 --> 01:04:41.834
I have a whole life ahead of me
and all that shit.

1110
01:04:41.965 --> 01:04:43.792
I am 65 years old.

1111
01:04:43.923 --> 01:04:46.795
I don't have a whole life
ahead of me.

1112
01:04:46.926 --> 01:04:50.799
I have a very small window
to be reckless.

1113
01:04:50.930 --> 01:04:54.455
to make decisions that feed this

1114
01:04:54.586 --> 01:04:56.849
and never factor this
into the equation.

1115
01:04:56.980 --> 01:04:58.633
And that's what I'm gonna do.

1116
01:04:58.764 --> 01:05:02.768
I'm gonna do what he begged me
to do for 30 years.

1117
01:05:04.291 --> 01:05:06.903
I'm gonna finally see
this place.

1118
01:05:11.211 --> 01:05:12.865
Want some company?

1119
01:05:13.039 --> 01:05:15.041
♪ slow. hopeful music ♪

1120
01:05:16.825 --> 01:05:18.697
I'd love some.

1121
01:05:21.004 --> 01:05:22.440
Well. then I'll see you
in the morning.

1122
01:05:22.570 --> 01:05:23.876
Okay.

1123
01:05:27.010 --> 01:05:28.489
[sniffles]

1124
01:05:38.673 --> 01:05:40.719
♪♪♪

1125
01:05:57.040 --> 01:05:58.563
[sighs. clicks tongue]

1126
01:05:58.693 --> 01:06:01.087
Poor choice of footwear
in retrospect.

1127
01:06:22.413 --> 01:06:24.415
♪♪♪

1128
01:06:36.296 --> 01:06:37.819
Okay.

1129
01:06:44.217 --> 01:06:46.089
[Russell]
I. personally. for the record.

1130
01:06:46.219 --> 01:06:49.918
feel that we are underdressed.
unarmed and just...

1131
01:06:50.049 --> 01:06:51.790
generally unprepared
for any kind of

1132
01:06:51.920 --> 01:06:53.879
exploratory venture afoot.

1133
01:06:54.010 --> 01:06:55.489
"Afoot."

1134
01:06:56.490 --> 01:06:58.753
I didn't know they taught
the Queen's English at Brown.

1135
01:06:58.884 --> 01:07:00.755
Well. they do. I mean.
I didn't actually study it.

1136
01:07:00.886 --> 01:07:02.496
but the-the course does exist.

1137
01:07:02.627 --> 01:07:06.500
Ah. And the world is
a better place for it. Russell.

1138
01:07:09.895 --> 01:07:11.940
Let's go find this spot.

1139
01:07:13.899 --> 01:07:15.944
♪♪♪

1140
01:07:35.660 --> 01:07:37.662
♪♪♪

1141
01:07:52.546 --> 01:07:54.548
♪ slow. dramatic music ♪
